<!-- BUSINESS ENTITY -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">1</div><div class="qtext">What is Business Entity Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>Imagine you run a small tea shop. You earn ₹10,000 from the shop. Now you take ₹2,000 from the shop's cash box for your personal groceries.<br><br>
    In accounting, we treat your <strong>shop as a completely different "person"</strong> from you the owner. So when you take ₹2,000, the shop records it as money going out — called "Drawings". The shop didn't "spend" on groceries — <em>you</em> did. The shop just lost ₹2,000 from its pocket.<br><br>
    This separation is the <strong>Business Entity Concept</strong> — the business has its own life, its own money, its own records — completely separate from the owner.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exambox">
    <div class="e-label">✍️ Write This in Exam</div>
    <p><strong>Business Entity Concept:</strong></p>
    <p>According to this concept, a business and its owner are treated as <strong>two separate and distinct entities</strong>. All accounting transactions are recorded from the point of view of the business, not the owner.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Even if a sole proprietor owns the business, his personal transactions are kept completely separate from business transactions. The business has its own assets, liabilities, and capital — independent of the owner's personal finances.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If the owner withdraws ₹10,000 for personal use, it is recorded as "Drawings" in the books of the business (reducing the owner's Capital account). It is NOT recorded as a business expense.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Importance:</strong> This concept ensures that financial statements of a business truly reflect the business performance — not mixed with the owner's personal finances.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- MONEY MEASUREMENT -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">2</div><div class="qtext">What is Money Measurement Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>Imagine your company has the world's best, most hardworking employees. They work 18 hours a day with full dedication. But can you write "Excellent Employee Morale" as an asset worth ₹50,00,000 in your balance sheet?<br><br>
    No — because <strong>you can't put a money value on it</strong>. Accounting only records things you can measure in rupees. If something has no price tag — it stays out of the books.<br><br>
    Similarly, a company's brand reputation, customer relationships, or future potential — all amazing things — are NOT recorded because we can't precisely measure them in money.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exambox">
    <div class="e-label">✍️ Write This in Exam</div>
    <p><strong>Money Measurement Concept:</strong></p>
    <p>According to this concept, only those transactions and events which can be <strong>expressed in terms of money</strong> are recorded in the books of accounts. Events that cannot be measured in monetary terms are not recorded.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Accounting deals with financial data only. Non-monetary events such as employee loyalty, brand reputation, management quality, or customer satisfaction — however important — are excluded because they cannot be given a definite monetary value.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A company has highly skilled and motivated employees. This cannot be recorded in books. However, if those employees' salaries are ₹5,00,000 per month — that is recorded because it has a monetary value.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Limitation:</strong> This concept ignores qualitative factors. It also assumes a stable monetary unit — but in reality, inflation changes the value of money over time.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- COST CONCEPT -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">3</div><div class="qtext">What is Cost Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>You bought a plot of land in 2010 for ₹5 lakhs. Today in 2025, that land is worth ₹50 lakhs. But in your company's books, the land is <strong>still shown as ₹5 lakhs</strong> — the price you actually paid.<br><br>
    Why? Because accounting wants to be <strong>objective and verifiable</strong>. The purchase price of ₹5 lakhs is a fact — there's a bill, a document, a proof. But ₹50 lakhs is just an estimate — different people will give different values. So we stick to the original cost.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exambox">
    <div class="e-label">✍️ Write This in Exam</div>
    <p><strong>Cost Concept (Historical Cost Concept):</strong></p>
    <p>According to this concept, all assets are recorded in the books of accounts at their <strong>original cost of acquisition (historical cost)</strong> and not at their current market value or replacement value.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> The cost at which an asset is purchased is the most objective and verifiable figure. If market values were used, different people would give different estimates, making financial statements unreliable. Historical cost ensures consistency and objectivity.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A company buys land for ₹5,00,000 in 2010. Even if the market value rises to ₹50,00,000 in 2025, the land continues to be shown in the Balance Sheet at ₹5,00,000 (less any depreciation if applicable).</p><br>
    <p><strong>Limitation:</strong> In times of inflation, historical cost becomes irrelevant. Assets are understated and profits may be overstated. This led to the development of Inflation Accounting.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ACCRUAL -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">4</div><div class="qtext">What is Accrual Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>You did plumbing work at someone's house in March. They will pay you in April. Should you count that income in March (when you did the work) or April (when you receive cash)?<br><br>
    <strong>Answer: March.</strong> Because you EARNED the money in March. The fact that cash came in April doesn't change when the work happened.<br><br>
    Similarly, your employees worked in March but you'll pay their salary in April. That salary expense belongs to March — because they worked in March.<br><br>
    This is Accrual — record when earned or incurred, not when cash moves.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exambox">
    <div class="e-label">✍️ Write This in Exam</div>
    <p><strong>Accrual Concept:</strong></p>
    <p>According to this concept, revenues are recognised when they are <strong>earned</strong> and expenses are recognised when they are <strong>incurred</strong> — regardless of when the actual cash is received or paid.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This concept forms the basis of accrual accounting (as opposed to cash accounting). It ensures that financial statements reflect the true financial performance of a period, not just when money physically changed hands.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example 1 (Income):</strong> Rent earned in March ₹5,000 but received in April → still recorded as income in March. Shown as "Accrued Rent" (Current Asset) in March Balance Sheet.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example 2 (Expense):</strong> Salary for March ₹10,000 paid in April → still recorded as March's expense. Shown as "Outstanding Salary" (Current Liability) in March Balance Sheet.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- MATCHING -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">5</div><div class="qtext">What is Matching Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>Imagine you made 100 samosas and sold 80 of them today. How many samosas' cost should you subtract from today's income?<br><br>
    Only 80 — the ones you actually SOLD. The remaining 20 samosas are sitting in your kitchen (closing stock). You'll sell them tomorrow and deduct their cost then.<br><br>
    This is Matching — match the cost of goods <strong>sold</strong> (not produced) against the revenue from those same goods. Don't mix today's sales with tomorrow's costs.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exambox">
    <div class="e-label">✍️ Write This in Exam</div>
    <p><strong>Matching Concept:</strong></p>
    <p>According to this concept, the revenues earned during an accounting period should be <strong>matched with the expenses incurred to earn those revenues</strong> in the same period. Only the cost of goods SOLD is matched against sales — not the cost of goods produced.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This concept is closely linked to the Accrual Concept. It prevents mixing of revenues and costs from different periods. Unsold goods are carried forward as Closing Stock (asset), not charged as expense in the current period.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A firm produces 1,000 units at a cost of ₹1,00,000 and sells 800 units for ₹1,20,000.<br>
    Cost matched against revenue = Cost of 800 units sold = ₹80,000 (not ₹1,00,000).<br>
    Cost of remaining 200 units = ₹20,000 → Closing Stock (shown as Current Asset in Balance Sheet).</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- GOING CONCERN -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">6</div><div class="qtext">What is Going Concern Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>You bought a laptop for ₹60,000 for your business. It will last 3 years. Each year you charge ₹20,000 as depreciation (cost spread over 3 years).<br><br>
    But WHY do we spread it over 3 years? Because we ASSUME the business will keep running for 3 more years and use the laptop all that time.<br><br>
    If we thought the business would shut down next month, we'd just write off the entire ₹60,000 immediately at liquidation (scrap) value.<br><br>
    The assumption that <strong>the business will keep going indefinitely</strong> — that's the Going Concern Concept.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exambox">
    <div class="e-label">✍️ Write This in Exam</div>
    <p><strong>Going Concern Concept:</strong></p>
    <p>According to this concept, it is assumed that a business enterprise will continue its operations <strong>indefinitely (for the foreseeable future)</strong> and will not be liquidated or forced to shut down in the near future.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This assumption justifies two key accounting treatments: (1) Assets are valued at historical cost (not liquidation/scrap value) because the business will continue using them. (2) The cost of long-term assets (like machinery) is spread over their useful life through depreciation — because the business will benefit from them over many years.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A machine purchased for ₹1,00,000 with a useful life of 10 years is depreciated at ₹10,000 per year. This is only logical if we assume the business will continue operating for 10 years.</p><br>
    <p><strong>Exception:</strong> If there is evidence that the business will shut down soon (insolvency, court orders), the Going Concern assumption is abandoned and assets are valued at their net realisable (liquidation) value.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- CONSERVATISM -->
<div class="qblock">
  <div class="qhead"><div class="qnum">7</div><div class="qtext">What is Conservatism (Prudence) Concept?</div><div class="qmarks">5 marks</div></div>
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="a-label">🧠 Understand It First — Real Life Analogy</div>
    <p>Think of a very careful, cautious person who plans for the worst. If they're going on a trip, they carry an umbrella even when the weather looks fine — "just in case it rains."<br><br>
    Accounting does the same thing. <strong>"Don't count your chickens before they hatch."</strong><br><br>
    If you expect a profit — don't record it until it's actually earned. But if you expect a loss — record it immediately, even if you're not 100% sure it will happen.<br><br>
    Example: You sold goods to a customer for ₹50,000. But you're not sure he'll pay (might be going bankrupt). Conservative accounting says — create a "provision for bad debt" immediately. Don't wait to find out if he actually defaults.</p>
  </div>
